{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bade541f-a065-4368-9818-32580d4cc662","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Args:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourServer`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug workflow:**\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke tools with sample inputs.\n- Use the **Resources** tab to browse exposed resources.\n- View raw JSON-RPC messages in the **Messages** pane for troubleshooting.\n\n**Key tips:**\n- Ensure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout only** — use `stderr` for any logging/diagnostics, or the Inspector won't parse the protocol correctly.\n- If your server needs environment variables, add them in the Inspector's **Environment Variables** section.\n- You can also pass `--no-build` in args if the project is already built, for faster iteration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dddc3291-7956-4be1-9f78-2db67fd58994","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to explore a codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"AC08:3434CB:B08F47:DC799D:6A012D55"},"id":"1de88685-e101-4879-be64-c790939bf2e8","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:14:09.824Z","parentId":"30c46db3-bad3-4f2b-8f84-cbbfaea917af"}
